segments.text: He said, take this plane and fly it straight back to Brooks.
And I said, well, I've never flown a plane.
He says, well, you won't learn any sooner.
No instructions at all.
And so he says, get that wing and that horizon.
And I kept climbing a little bit, or I'd be going down.
I couldn't hold that thing.
He says, who in there blankety-blank ever told you you would fly?
And after a while, he took over when we got pretty close to Brooks.
And he throttled the motor, of course, going down the land.
And we were going over past this tower.
And I saw some of them later.
And Bob Williams, who later became a major general, he says,
Oh, didn't Breen, did you draw Breen as an indirect?
I said, I sure did.
And I got chewed out this morning.
He said, I heard every word you said.
When you're coming over that, coming over this barracks and come down, he said, I happened to be in.
And I had heard every word he told you.
And everybody else, because he had that deep voice, you know, and he always cussed.
Well, uh...
They called me down for physical right after that.
And I went in there, and Captain Hart, who was a medical examiner, he had been to a special course on the heart at Harvard University, a refresher course.
He caught three of us, one student from Vanderbilt and the other one from Georgia Tech and myself.
I was the only Texas, there were 12 of us from Texas down there on active duty.
We were second lieutenants.
And all three of us, and they gave us another chance.
Caught three of you what?
With a bad heart.
Oh, with a bad heart.
Irregular heart.
So he says, now, Captain Hart says, come back.
And he says, asked me, he said, you been hedgehogged?
Have you been on a flight this morning?
I said, I sure have.
And he says, who's your instructor?
I told him, he said, well, you come back for another physical.
I'll give you a break.
And he gave me an apartment.
And I went back again, and same one.
He says, I've had irregular heart evidence all my life.
And I went, my uncle checked me after I got home.
And he says, I can't find the thing wrong.
And I'm.
So they discharged you?
Oh, yeah.
I got a discharge.
So they got a medical discharge then from active duty in the Army.
Yeah, they wanted me to transfer to the quartermaster.
But I had made up my mind if I was going to take this active duty, and then I was coming back to A&M the following semester, the following year.
And when they wanted to transfer me to the quartermaster, I said I'd prefer not.
So I got out.
And then you went back to A&M.
I came back, and I've been here ever since.
And you decided then that you wanted to go into vet school?
Yes.
I'd made up my mind.
I'd had two courses, one under Dr. Francis.
As an undergraduate?
In anatomy, oh yes, in veterinary medicine.
And then, and a course under Dr. Ornstein and Dr. Leonard as a senior.
made up my mind, I'd like to try it.
Did you ever, even though you had made up your mind that you wanted to become a vet, did you ever think of going to some other vet school?
No, not at the time, because this probably was the cheapest school.
Oh, sure.
And another thing, I was a great admirer of Dr. Francis.
Well, we're going to talk about him in a minute, and so I want to ask you another question.
And that concerns the screening process for your entrance into vet school.
Can you tell me how that worked at the time?
They didn't screen you.
When you applied.
All you needed back in those days was, I think, 17 credits or something like that from high school to enter as a freshman in veterinary medicine.
I had this degree and I didn't have any screening process like I have now.
Yeah.
So they were quite happy to have you as a student.
Well, they didn't have.
I think there were Sure, there were so few.
In the class ofI finished in January of 26.
I was the only one at that time.
Then they had, I think, three to finish in May in 26.
Jaggie was one of them.
and J.D.
Jones and Paul Bariski, the three graduates in 26.
That is in May.
And I took most of my work, however, with the class of 25, and then left off, of course, in clinic so I could come back, and I asked Dr. Marstittle if I could do it, and they said sure.
So I left that one course to take, say,
and take an extra semester.
But I worked at the veterinary hospital.
I lived down there and had lived down there since 24.
Well, did they help you, fund you somehow?
Did they give you sort of a work-study situation, or how did you support yourself?
Well, I was getting 25 cents an hour like everybody else.
I finally got up to, I think by the time I finished in January of 26, I was getting 31 cents an hour.
That was pretty good.
The blacks and the others, the laborers, and they usually had six or eight or ten of them, they were getting 33 cents an hour.
The one, the Negro who took the part.
And they were doing construction around?
No, taking care of the dogs or the horses and the cattle and the hogs.
Hauling mess haul garbage.
They usually had several hundred hogs they would feed with mess haul garbage.
And ship them off to a market.
I remember a number of cases.
I was at the hospital with Dr. Marsteller, who was dean at that time.
No, he wasn't dean.
Dr. Francis was the dean, but he was next in line.
He was head of medicine and surgery.
He'd wake us up about 5, 30 in the morning.
Says, let's go on.
Let's get going.
Said, we're going to load those hogs this morning.
And usually I'd have noticed the night before, but the day before.
But we drove hogs from the old hospital right across from where the AG building, the old AG building is now.
That old hospital, of course, was torn down in 1933.
And then the barns over here extended out where all they play polo and that around that area now.
But we drive them from that hospital up by where it is, the old chemistry building, where the archives building is now, the old Cushing Library, right by the academic building.
Between that and the physics building and the civil engineering, old civil engineering building at least.
I don't know what they have there now, history, I think.
and then by Goodwin Hall, and I hope the Koch Building was not there, but right across there, and just get there a little after daybreak, and of course, pardon me, just before Reveille.
And you could hear the boys.
We had one old Tom Hill,
would take a sack of corn and lead them, and they'd follow him.
He'd be throwing corn on the way.
But those hogs, of course, they were fat hogs.
They would grunt, and the boys would start calling, suey, suey, right from Goodwin Hall and from Foster Hall.
But...
course I don't think anybody's living around the Y and I am not sure whether they had, I don't believe they had that tenth cent in it anymore.
I don't know where the low end per year were in at the time, I don't think so.
But we'd drive them down to the Missouri Pacific right across the drill field, parade ground now, down by where the
Across Wellborn Road there?
Yes, right across that and load them right at the Missouri Pacific Station.
I'd have a car there and we'd load them.
But I remember doing that several times.
And that's the kind of work that you would do for your 25 cents an hour?
Well, take care of clinic horses and cattle, any dogs, anything else they had.
But it was a wonderful experience.
Yeah, I would think.
I think it would be excellent.
Where did you live?
I was there in the hospital right next to the dog ward.
Really?
Yes.
Did you get much sleep?
Well, you learn to do with it.
Did they put most of the vet students up?
No, I was the only one down there.
Well, we had one boy, Harvey Ellis, lived in the other part further away.
But I was right next to the dog ward and next to the,
the Dr. Marsteller's office, Dr. Leonard's office, at the entrance.
And every night that owl would come through here about 12, 20, but before you could ever hear the whistle, it would be down around Weldon.
The dogs would start howling.
You usually have one dog to lead them.
And they'd start howling.
Well, you didn't know the owl was coming.
Another time, 1.30, well, I had
probably asleep by then.
And then the morning trains, they'd howl.
Of course, that's at high note before a person could hear them.
They could detect it.
And they'd all howl.
So you always knew if the trains were on time.
No, they didn't wake me up once I got to sleep.
Not after that.
I got used to it.
You got used to it?
Oh, yeah.
You slept right through that?
Yeah.
What did you think of your student colleagues in the vet school?
I know there were only a few of them, but what do you think their quality was, or compare them to more recent students?
Well, some of them did some, made very good citizens and did good jobs when they got out.
I don't know.
One boy dropped out as a junior.
I don't know what ever happened to Robbins.
But the rest of them stayed with veterinary medicine in one form or another.
And a couple in that class of 25 became quite wealthy, one from real estate and the other one from organizing this company at
peanutizing company at Fort Worth that Bill Anderson bought it from his widow.
But he used to, that boy used to work at the horse barn.
He was a poor boy, but he became a millionaire out of that thing.
And so financially wise, those two boys out of that class of 25
perhaps have been very successful, of course.
Winchester from Texarkana said there were three millionaires in that class of 25, and two of them were vet students.
And, but I think he bought the land right there in the age of Texarkana.
And because
I know that McDonald's was trying to buy some land from him.
He wouldn't sell to them.
He didn't know.
But I don't know what happened.
Were they pretty good students?
Yes, they were pretty good students.
Did you detect any change over the years of the quality of the students?
Oh, after we got to screening them, and the first class that was screened was the class of 50, 1950.
In fact, when they made, see, we had about a quadruple increase about 1932.
In fact, we had only one student in 30, that was Ty Hardy.
And two students in 28, and I think three in 27, and four in 20.
Let's see, in 22, 21, there were four or five.
And 23, there were two.
22, there were two.
And there, several years, only one would graduate.
But in 32, the student enrollment jumped about four times many, and then in 38, it jumped again.
So they made a ruling in about 40, at 39 or 40, that the enrollment would be limited to 100 students.
And then in 45 or 46, I'm not positive about the exact time.
Anyway, they made a ruling that each class would be screened according to scholarship and aptitude.
Those were the two qualities they were putting on there.
So that made the class of 50 the first one that had been screened.
And the quality was pretty good.
But grade point-wise, I often think these high schools change their grading, and some of them from schools that are more lenient than others.
I remember a boy came here with a straight A average, and he didn't get the first base here.
I never got into the sophomore year.
But I think that was aptitude.
That was before they started screening them.
So his brother, no, his father was a veterinarian.
And so he was sent.
It was mandatory.
And he just wasn't beginning to take to it.
No, he wasn't.
I didn't understand.
He was out of pocket.
So, but these students nowadays, their grade point ratio is pretty high.
They had some masters and PhDs even have come through.
In fact, I've had several PhDs that came through.
One happened to be a memorizer.
In fact, I went back and studied his history at the lowest grade.
grade in the class.
I'd forgotten how many we had that year, about 60, and he had the lowest.
He made, he was the only one below 70, and he made a grade of 58, I think.
And I couldn't understand it.
And he came around and asked me to give him part of something to study.
I says, look, a man with a PhD, don't you ask me how to study.
I said, you'd better go somewhere else.
I said, I can't give you any leads.
I said, I can tell you this, you're a memorizer.
And I said, you can't see the forest for the trees.
And I said, get with somebody who takes notes and can pay attention.
I don't know whether he was paying attention.
I think he was glorying in that he'd just received his PhD.
But he took it in taxonomy.
I found and later checked on him, and some of them said, he got it on taxonomy, which is rote memory.
I said, well, that explains it.
I said, when it comes to thought questions, he can't do it.
I said, they'll find him out in clinic.
And he was found out in clinic.
He made C's.
And everybody else was making B's and A's.
But that was an exception.
That just stands out like a sore thumb to me.
But just to show you the quality, I think he was a crybaby.
And I had been warned by others who taught him as a freshman, sophomore that he's been crying on your shoulder for a grade or something.
And he had to work like everything to get a C with me.
And he was trying to talk me out of a beat.
I said, no way.
I said, you're a C student.
And I said, your record shows that you've never made higher than a C. And I said, you surely haven't done better than a C with me.
But I warned another student, one of the girls who came to me, about him being so good that I'd been studying with him.
I said, well, get away from him.
I said, he's the only class, he's like the lowest grade in class.
I said, do your own thinking.
And I said, you're a memorizer too.
And I said, I'm going to start asking questions that are not out of the book.
Thought questions for you people.
I said, I'm going to change my type of attack.
And
So they started making lower grades.
But they finally worked out.
They were two in the same class.
But in general, what would you say is the quality of the students?
Very good.
In fact, I had lots of As.
And I wasn't known to give an A or many As.
But I had quite a few of them.
And I remember one class in the 40s.
before we started screening them, that we had too many for one section.
I had around 90, I think, 80 or 90.
And I said, well, we're going to divide it into two sections in lecture.
And I couldn't get them.
There were a bunch of students that wouldn't fit.
What do you mean they wouldn't fit?
Nine, they wouldn't fit the schedule.
Oh.
And if I had just put two and two together, they were flunkies, and they had such an irregular schedule, there were nine of them.
And I had, or eight.
Every one but one had an F at the end of the semester.
Hold on.
No, I had seven F's and two D's or C's.
I forgot what a passing grade was then.
So it bothered me, and we always had a correlation between physiology, my courses, and the chemistry and the biology.
So I went to Dr. Haddish.
He said, don't bother.
He said, when we get classes in here, the majority of them flunk.
Well, that was true in freshman chemistry.
And we took those same students and found out that all nine of them flunked chemistry.
And I went to the biology.
All nine of them flunked biology.
I said, well, I'm a softy.
I said, I passed two of them.
The other two, and believe it or not, in the largest of the three sections, there were a bunch of buddies in there and they all got together.
All the A's were in that section, in the largest.
And I had a bunch of A's.
So I learned a lot about teaching.
These boys, these nine students, were about two weeks behind the other two sections when we got through.
I just had to skim through part of it.
No wonder.
I let them set their own pace.
In this large section, they were going higher than the second, but I learned better.
Tell me about how difficult you thought the course work was in 1923 and 24.
Well, I think for one thing they let us take too much work, sign up too many hours.
And I think that gave rise to the limiting the number of hours that they could take.
In the 30s, we did that in the 30s.
I mean, you could take any, back in the 20s, you could take as many hours as you wanted.
Dr. Francis, who was a dean, he says, you do a whole lot better work if you're busy.
So you want any more courses on that?
I'll just give you more.
That's what he said.
That was his attitude.
So as a result, why, some of us overloaded.
I would think so.
But I learned, man.
less than the hard way.
But when they started limiting the number of hours, I don't recall what year, that was in the late 20s or early 30s, they did that.
But that helped a lot.
Did you find the coursework very difficult, or do you think it's increased
difficulty over the years?
It should be more difficult now because the student now has so much more to learn.
And with all the research, it's far better now.
Of course, as we got larger and larger, the students got less contact with the clinical animals, but they have a very efficient way of handling clinic now.
It's much better, the curriculum is much better than it was back in those days.
In what way is it more, is it better?

Well, working in small groups in these clinic groups of six or eight students or something like that, and back in, oh, in the middle 30s or 40s where you'd have large groups, and they didn't have it organized as well as they do now.
Of course, we didn't have satisfactory textbooks for most courses.
We had a good one in physiology, and we didn't have a good one in pharmacology.
We had nothing in toxicology.
So we had to more or less make our own notes, lecture notes, out of journals.
And some of the other books, some foreign books and lab manuals, were practically
unknown and so we had to more or less write our own lab instructions.
But we all learned from it, managed it somehow.
I was wondering about when you were a student in the mid-1920s, who were your favorite instructors?
Well some in animal husbandry and later in veterinary medicine, but some of them out.
I would say Dr. Silvey, head of the physics department, was one of my favorites.
Dr. Bilsing, head of entomology, was one of my favorites.
Mr. Stangle, W.L.
Stangle, we called him Runt.
He was later dean head of Allen Vesbury and Dean at Texas Tech.
Mr. George Templeton, who was head of the department for several years, left here and went to Mississippi.
And then Dr. Francis in veterinary medicine was one of the greatest
probably the greatest man I've ever known.
In fact, that's one reason I came back here, to teach.
I wanted to take three years of graduate work with him, or teach.
But I worked with him and under him for 10 years before he died in 36.
Well, let's talk about Dr. Mark Francis now.
Tell me about your relationship with him.
Well, he was the dean and head of anatomy.
When I came here in 26, there were six teachers, and I think there were four wives, Mrs. Francis, Mrs. Marstella,
Mrs. Leonard and Mrs. Wharton.
Wharton was in pathology.
But there were six of us teaching, three of them in veterinary medicine surgery, one in pathology, one in anatomy, and one in physiology.
And now
They have over 100 teaching staff and about 150 or more in the classified personnel, that is technicians.
We didn't have a single technician in the 20s.
One telephone, one stenographer or secretary
She was at the dean's office in the mornings and then with the veteran of medicine and surgery in the afternoons.
And if I had to write a letter, well, I had to get it in the morning or either write it that day or that evening and then have it at her desk in the morning so she could type it.
And no technicians.
But we had one
